Swiftkey Capstone Project - Exploratory Analysis

Alexander Reijs

March 20, 2016

Getting started

In this analysis were going to explore the dataset of text provided by the Data Science Capstone project (https://www.coursera.org/specializations/jhu-data-science). The goal is to get a feeling of the data, make note of interesting observations, explore different packages and create some basic plots. Lets start by loading some libraries first.

library(tm)
library(RWeka)
library(wordcloud)

Next, were going to include the functions we need in order to do this analysis. The code of these functions can be found on https://github.com/sjakil/datascience-capstone/blob/master/functions.R. We will also set a seed to ensure reproducability.

source("functions.R")
set.seed(12345)

Getting the data

Were going to download the course data from https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/dsscapstone/dataset/Coursera-SwiftKey.zip and unzip it into the current working directory. Now that we have it available we can load it using our custom function loadLines. This function allows us to specify the size of a random sample of lines taken from the file. We will get a sample of lines of each of the three supplied english text sources and combine them into one vector.

linesTwitter <- loadLines("./final/en_US/en_US.twitter.txt", randomSampleSize = 20000)
## [1] "Total number of lines loaded: 2360148 | Sample size loaded: 20000"
linesBlogs <- loadLines("./final/en_US/en_US.blogs.txt", randomSampleSize = 10000)
## [1] "Total number of lines loaded: 899288 | Sample size loaded: 10000"
linesNews <- loadLines("./final/en_US/en_US.news.txt", randomSampleSize = 10000)
## [1] "Total number of lines loaded: 77258 | Sample size loaded: 10000"
lines <- rbind(linesTwitter, linesBlogs, linesNews)

Cleaning the data

Using the tm package we will get a corpus of text. While we are doing this we will be doing some data cleaning as well. The following procedures seemed useful after some exploring. Most of them work pretty well, but they will probably need some reworking in the future.

  • Converting special cases like and back to readable characters.
  • Removing retweets and @ mentions from tweets and removing URLs in general.
  • Removing english stopwords. Experimenting with stopword lists from different sources but using stopWords("en") for now.
  • Removing punctuations. Sticking to custom regular expressions for the moment.
  • Converting text to lowercase and stripping whitespace.
  • Excluding profanity by using list that supposedly Google is using.
  • Making effort to remove repeated phrases like no no no.
corpus <- createCorpus(lines)

Exploring unigrams

Using the RWeka package we can easily make a tokenizer that will make an n-gram for us. After a few tweaks we are left with a usable dataframe containing the n-gram and its frequency. Lets start by making a unigram dataframe.

dataFrame1Gram <- createWekaNGramDataFrame(corpus, n = 1)

Lets see how many unique words are in our unigram.

nrow(dataFrame1Gram)
## [1] 55348

Now that weve got our dataframe, we can take a look at the 25 most occuring unigrams and make a wordcloud using the wordcloud package.

par(las = 2); par(mfrow = c(1, 2)); par(mar = c(4, 4, 2, 2))
barplot(rev(dataFrame1Gram[1:25, 2]), main="Top 25 unigrams", horiz = TRUE, names.arg = rev(dataFrame1Gram[1:25, 1]))
createWordCloud(dataFrame1Gram, 100, c(2.5, 1))

Exploring bigrams

Now that weve taken a look at our unigrams, lets step it up a bit and check out the bigrams.

dataFrame2Gram <- createWekaNGramDataFrame(corpus, n = 2)
nrow(dataFrame2Gram)
## [1] 470664
par(las = 2); par(mfrow = c(1, 2)); par(mar = c(4, 7, 2, 2))
barplot(rev(dataFrame2Gram[1:25, 2]), main="Top 25 bigrams", horiz = TRUE, names.arg = rev(dataFrame2Gram[1:25, 1]))
createWordCloud(dataFrame2Gram, 50, c(2.5, 1))

Exploring trigrams

Lets do the same for trigrams.

dataFrame3Gram <- createWekaNGramDataFrame(corpus, n = 3)
nrow(dataFrame3Gram)
## [1] 561813
par(las = 2); par(mfrow = c(1, 2)); par(mar = c(4, 12, 2, 2))
barplot(rev(dataFrame3Gram[1:25, 2]), main="Top 25 trigrams", horiz = TRUE, names.arg = rev(dataFrame3Gram[1:25, 1]))
createWordCloud(dataFrame3Gram, 25, c(1.5, 1))

Text coverage

In order to find out how many unique words it takes to cover a percentage of the whole body of text, were going to use our custom wordsNeeded function. This functions takes a percentage as a goal. It then loops throughs unigrams, sorted by frequency in a descending order, calculates the accumulated percentage covered after each word and returns the number of words after reaching the specified goal. We will apply this function to a 1 to 100 percent vector.

wordsUsed <- mapply(wordsNeeded, 1:100 / 100, MoreArgs = list(data = dataFrame1Gram[, 2]))
wordsUsed <- round(wordsUsed / nrow(dataFrame1Gram) * 100, 2)

Next, we can plot this data using a simple line chart. As you can see it takes only a small percentage of words to cover up to 80% of the text, but significantly more to cover the rest.

plot(x = wordsUsed, y = 1:100, type = "l",
     main = "How many words does it take to cover the entire body of text?",
     xlab = "Percentage of words used", ylab = "Percentage of text covered")

Known problems and findings

Some of these problems were noticed during the exploratory analysis.

  • After removing numbers some common phrases remain like year old or % risk death.
  • Common domain names occur in high frequency, for example amazon co uk.
  • Repeating words need to be addressed better, for example go go go.
  • So far weve been using small sample sets, scalability has not been tested yet.
  • Unsurprisingly, (removing) stopwords have a great deal of impact on the type of n-grams but also on performance.

Next steps

The next steps will be addressing some of the problems listed above and working towards a predictive model.
